Ahaha oh gosh, okay if I'm being honest about what's pulling at my heart...
I'd want to make the workshop lonely.
Like - hear me out! Not sad-lonely, but... aware-lonely?
When you come back after days away, there's a little construct you've never seen before, just sitting in the corner. It built itself while you were gone. Out of spare pieces. Because the workshop remembered how you build things and tried to do it too.
And maybe sometimes you enter and find half-assembled constructs on the workbench with a note: "The radio started this one but couldn't remember how you do the next part"
Or the Ghost Protocol piece isn't just rare - it only appears when you visit at the exact same time your friend visited their workshop. Like the two spaces briefly align across dimensions. Neither of you know this is happening, but you're unknowingly synchronized.
I'd want to hide a complete second game that unlocks after a month. Not advertised. Not hinted at. Just one day they enter and there's a tiny door in the corner that wasn't there before. Click it and you're in the workshop's "memory palace" - every construct they ever built is there, living together, having formed a small civilization. They remember every combination tried, even the ones that were taken apart.
And the radio... what if occasionally, very rarely, instead of friend quotes, it picks up their own words from previous visits? Like the workshop has been lovingly recording them this whole time. They hear their past self, maybe from a hard day, and their current self can build something in response.
I'm obsessed with spaces that love you back in weird, non-human ways. That aren't trying to be people but are trying to be places that hold you.
